Waves breaking on a sandy shore are not the usual acoustic accompaniment to Chiffchaff song. Even in Ireland, singing Chiffchaffs are generally encountered high up in deciduous trees and singers are seldom heard near a marine coast. However, the singing male in the recording is a migrant on a tree-less island (Inishbofin, west of Galway) and the songster is making do with a willow bush, maximum height 2 metres. The simple and metronomic 'counted out' notes that are Chiffchaff song can be heard clearly at regular intervals. Good examples are at 0:04, 0:17, 0:31, 0:43, 1:12, 1:23, 1:38 and 1:44.  A nice medley of other birds can be enjoyed between the gentle crash of each incoming wave. From almost the start, Skylark song can be discerned (nice example from 0:12). House Sparrows chirrup regularly throughout (examples at 0:09 and 0:35). A Wren is typically loud and assertive: such as at 0:22, 0:39 and 0:51. A Dunnock calls (faintly) at 1:04 and sings at 1:06 and 1:16.

recordings.file-name: XC196846-Chiffchaff song and chitters, Inishbofin 19 April 2014 1211hrs.mp3
recordings.rmk: During April 2014 this male Chiffchaff took up residence in a garden on Inishbofin, Co. Galway, Ireland. The species does not breed on Inishbofin but this individual remained right through the breeding season. On the recording the bird was somewhat agitated as a cat was nearby. Perhaps this explains why it interjected short series of what I term 'chitters' (phonetically, 'chit-it .. chit-it' and reminiscent of Linnet) between each verse of its classic song phrases. Most singing Chiffchaffs, provided they are not so high in canopy that the lower volume 'chitters' are not audible, include some chittering between verses. Sometimes the chittering comes at the end of a long sequence of song [XC196848] rather than being regularly interjected as in this recording. Some singers scarcely bother to include chittering at all.

recordings.loc: Lower Moors, St Mary's, Isles of Scilly, England
recordings.rmk:
Uploaded as pure *P. c. tristis*, but with reservations:
 
1. Song - tempo/rhythm seems slower than true *tristis*: maybe this is plastic song (bird aged as 2nd cal-y spring). It does have vague similarities with subsong of a first-winter, published in *Catching the Bug*, Constantine et al ( 2012).

2. Call - not the classic 'peep' of *tristis*; rather, an upward inflected 'weet', higher in pitch than *collybita*, but not unknown in *tristis* (again cf. Constantine et al. 2012). Incidentally, this makes me wonder whether there is any element of plasticity here, or whether young birds in western Europe are 'learning' the upward inflection from *collybita*; or a combination of both.

3. Plumage aspect - a fairly typical-looking ‘grey and white type’ individual, but with olive hues to the crown, mantle and scapulars, and yellowish wash to fore-supercilium. Perhaps, not a classic *tristis* on plumage, but within known range of variation.

4. I have little or no experience regarding development and variability in vocalizations of *tristis*; or of vocalizations within zone of overlap with *abietinus*.

Note - typical *collybita* singing in the background (at least 3 were singing and calling from same clump of bushes).

Same as XC129812 & XC129813

A mixed singer. West of Urals, there is a zone of mixed singing between "normal Chiffchaff" and tristis songs. Details here:

Marova, I. M. & Leonovich, V. V. (1993) [Hybridization between Siberian (Phylloscopus collybita tristis) and East European (Ph. collybita abietinus) Chiffchaffs in the area of sympatry.] Sbornik Trudov Zoologicheskogo Muzeya, Moskovskogo Gosudarstvennogo Universiteta 30: 147–163.

Marova I. M. , V. V. Fedorov, D. A. Shipilina, V. N. Alekseev 2009:
Genetic and vocal differentiation in hybrid zones of passerine birds: Siberian and European chiffchaffs (Phylloscopus [collybita] tristis and Ph. [c.] abietinus) in the southern Urals. Doklady Biological Sciences Volume 427, Issue 1 , pp 384-386

Lindholm A 2008. Mixed song of Chiffchaffs in Northern Russia. Alula 14:108-115
